metadata.name: Omega Point #7
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #2
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Reveries Automata #66
metadata.description:
"The lifetime of a being translated into dualistic combinations. Each individual maintains their perspective of things. Each individual has its pillars and its interferences. A life without concerns can be cleaner and quieter, but undeniably a little chaos can add to the beauty of a whole. It's all about it. Order. Chaos. Singularity is precious. Differences are our riches. Royal beings."

"Reveries Automata" is a generative project that combines AI Art with creative coding. This project was made to be minted on Fxhash and it's inspired on my previous collection "Reveries" where I explore the abstract nuances of art using diffusion models.

I wanted to explore this field of image composition inside creative coding. The solution I came up with was to reveal the images using coded masks.
There are 3 main functions for that:

The Pillars - made basically tiling a separate layer proportionally in the canvas with random sizes, position and rotation (just 2 options for this one, 0 or 90 degrees). Then using this layer as a mask to my base image. Tinted in the colors white, black, blue, red, gold or green.

The Splashes -  A function that makes random ellipses around the canvas in a separate layer, attached in the back and front pillar. And, again, using this layer as a mask to my base image. Tinted in the same color the pillar received.

The Interferences - Probably the one that gave me more trouble to adapt. This funcion is a flow field that uses the color and brightness of my base image to draw and color itself. First I plot particles to use as initial position of the flow and make them draw based on the difference in brightness of my base image. The flow is coloured getting the pixel position of that base image. Tinted in the colors white, gold or black.

To support those code functions and to make sure that the outputs will have many variations, I've prompted and composited 40 base images that are used as background, patterns, textures, flow drawing/colouring and frames.

There are concrete textures, painting flow textures and golden foil textures for background and pillars; Rough contrasted painting flows (white and gold) for the interferences; Labyrinth, Rectangular and Copacabana patterns; 6 paper frames variations to finalize the composition.

Press "G" to save currebt .png canvas.

Read more about: https://brunomerli.com/reveries-automata

metadata.name: Almost #201
metadata.description:
Hello, I am a 13-year-old girl who has put together this image-composition project for my project-based-learning end-of-term project.  This term we learned about biodiversity and how biodiversity loss affects us and the world around us.  All the images in this project are hand-drawn (on an iPad) by me.

I will be donating all proceeds from the minting of this project to plant trees.  Secondary royalties will be kept by me.  Thank you all ahead of time for your support!

metadata.name: Deep Forest #300
metadata.description:
I love being in nature and impressionistic paintings. Deep Forest is my latest attempt to combine them with JavaScript. The editions will range from open, sparse forests to lush, dense, leafy wonderlands. Fall editions may render as Klimpt-style birch forests - my original inspiration for this work.

Best viewed on a computer. It may take a few seconds to start drawing and, depending on complexity, several minutes to finish rendering. In live view, press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px.

Features:
- One of the four seasons
- Rare 10% night version with 50/50 for normal fireflies or "fire" fireflies. Night will only be spring or summer.
- Amount of atmosphere/haze
- Horizon line near the middle or 30% "high horizon" near the top
- Tint from one of 8 light and 7 shadow colors
- Strength of the light and shadow color tint
- Mixed tree trunks or 30% all birch
- 50/50 moss on tree trunks
- One of 8 flower colors in spring or summer
- One of 4 perspective transforms
- Straight, curved out, or 30% curved inward trunks
- 50/50 grass in fall or winter
- 85% will have flowers in spring and summer
- 95% will have underbrush
- 50/50 clouds or solid background
- 50/50 solid background will be vertical or swirls
- Ground hill height

metadata.name: Cradle #276
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

metadata.name: Before/After #93
metadata.description:
A visual representation of a non-linear transformation. Each line connects a data point before the transformation has been applied to its corresponding point after the transformation has been applied. Switch to debug mode to see the untransformed and transformed points. Outline mode shows only the lines and can be used for plotting. (Plotting will likely work best on outputs where the total number of lines is low.)

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive transformation (t-SNE) implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. The final artwork is a static SVG file that can be downloaded and displayed at any resolution. No external libraries have been used.

More information about this collection is provided here: https://clauswilke.com/art/project/before-after

I would like to thank Bartholomew Littlesilver for helpful artistic feedback, Liam Egan for help with creating plottable SVGs, and BRUTALISTI and neophob for encouraging me to pursue AssemblyScript for implementing performance-critical code.

Press 'm' to cycle between normal, debug, and outline mode.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

Long, Thin, Tubular Structure

- Using WEBGL1.0
- Textures/Images: None
- 3D Model data: None
- Library: None
- Vertex Shader: 1
- Fragment Shader: 1


Note:
Keyboard m key: Opens the menu. You can save the resolution and the image.
Keyboard f key: fit the screen.
The minimum resolution is 1600px x1600px, but no upper limit is set. The limit is determined by your machine and browser.

GPU is required because of WebGL.

metadata.name: FEA #108
metadata.description:
Soft - Light - Vivid - Zen - Diverse

Feathers are unique.

They served different aspects of purposes and holds different stories of the bird.

Reimagine the formation of the feather via code.
You will see the feather hairs' growing along the spine in an animated manner.

Various patterns both from real and digital worlds were sampled.
Peacock / Dotted / Natural Graident / Digital Lerp with different color combinations.

A Special pattern called FXpunk with percentage is also introduced to pay respect to everyone@FX.

Part of the royalties to the Minter & Processing Foundation

NOTE: 
best view -> 16:9 window size in a large display. 
best view -> open Live window -> expand window size -> refresh the work
press S to export the work.
